==English==

===Etymology===
The name was coined by Charles de Brosses in ''Histoire des navigations aux terres australes'' 1756. He derived it from the [[Latin]] for "south of [[Asia]]" 

===Proper noun===
'''Australasia'''

# A somewhat ambiguous term that relates variously to a physical geographical region or political geographical region that is variously defined:-


In political geography:-
* A region consisting of Australia and islands of the south west Pacific ''(The Australian Concise Oxford Dictionary)''
* Australia, New Zealand, and neighbouring islands of the the South Pacific Ocean ''(The Concise Macquarie Dictionary)''
* Occasionally used to designate [[Oceania]], which includes all the islands of the [[Pacific Ocean]]. ''((Funk & Wagnalls New Encyclopedia, 1971)''
* Often used to refer to just Australia and New Zealand  ''(THE HUMAN GENETICS SOCIETY OF AUSTRALASIA -  “Australasia” or “Australasian” pertains to Australia and New Zealand.)''


In physical geography:-
* Australia, New Guinea, New Zealand and other nearby islands. ''(The World Book Encyclopedia 1971)''
* designation sometimes applied to all the lands and islands of the Pacific Ocean lying between equator and latitude 47deg south. ''((Funk & Wagnalls New Encyclopedia, 1971)''


From a biological point of view:-
*the Australasia ecozone is a distinct region with a common evolutionary history and a great many unique plants and animals, some of them common to the entire area, others specific to particular parts but sharing a common ancestry. 
